      <byline class="print_byline">By Timothy Pritchard</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Pritchard, Timothy</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Price of nickel falls 11 percent to $4.15 a pound on metal markets after 3,400 mine and smelter workers at Inco Ltd in Sudbury, Ontario, reach tentative agreement to new three-year labor contract (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The price of nickel fell 11 percent to $4.15 a pound on metal markets after 3,400 mine and smelter workers at Inco Ltd. in Sudbury, Ontario, reached a tentative agreement over the weekend on a new three-year labor contract. Speculators, betting on a strike that would further tighten nickel supplies, had driven up the price in recent weeks. Inco produces more than one-quarter of the world's nickel</p>
        <p>Timothy Pritchard (NYT)</p>
      </block>
